<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="s_subgroups" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Subgroups</title>

    <definition xml:id="d_subgroup">
    <title>Subgroup</title>
    <notation>
        <usage><m>H\leq G</m></usage>
      <description><m>H</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m></description>
    </notation>
    <statement>
    <p>
    A <term>subgroup</term> of a group <m>G</m> is a subset <m>H\subseteq G</m> satisfying the following properties. 
    <ol marker="(i)">
        <li>
            <title>Identity element</title>
            <p>
                <m>e\in H</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <title>Closed under group law</title>
            <p>
                For all <m>g_1,g_2\in G</m>, if <m>g_1,g_2\in H</m>, then <m>g_1g_2\in H</m>. Using logical shorthand: 
                <men xml:id="eq_subgrp_prod">
                    g_1,g_2\in H\implies g_1g_2\in H
                </men>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <title>Closed under inverses</title>
            <p>
                For all <m>g\in G</m>, if <m>g\in H</m>, then <m>g^{-1}\in H</m>. Using logical shorthand:
                <men xml:id="eq_subgrp_inverses">
                    g\in H\implies g^{-1}\in H
                </men>.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    We write <m>H\leq G</m> to denote that <m>H</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m>. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <remark>
    <title>Subgroup</title>
    <p>
    There are common equivalent variations of <xref ref="d_subgroup"/>. For example we could define a subgroup of <m>G</m> to be a subset <m>H</m> satisfying the following conditions. 
    <ol marker="(i)">
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>H\ne \emptyset</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                For all <m>g_1,g_2\in G</m>, if <m>g_1,g_2\in H</m>, then <m>g_1^{-1}g_2\in H</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    Such equivalent versions have the advantage of brevity. I prefer <xref ref="d_subgroup"/> as it makes more evident the important result of <xref ref="prop_subgrp_is_grp"/>: namely, that subgroups are themselves examples of groups. 
    </p>
    </remark>
    <proposition xml:id="prop_subgrp_is_grp">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>(G, \cdot)</m> be a group and suppose <m>H</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m>.
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Restricting the group operation <m>\cdot</m> to <m>H</m> defines a binary operation 
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\boldsymbol{\cdot}_H\colon H\times H \amp \rightarrow H</mrow>
                                <mrow>(h_1,h_2) \amp \mapsto h_1\boldsymbol{\cdot}_H h_2=h_1\cdot h_2</mrow>
                            </md>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The pair <m>(H, \boldsymbol{\cdot}_H)</m> is a group. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The only issue here is whether the output of the proposed operation <m>\boldsymbol{\cdot}_H</m> actually land in <m>H</m>, and this is guaranteed by axiom (ii) of <xref ref="d_subgroup"/>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Since <m>\boldsymbol{\cdot}_H</m> is just the restriction of <m>\cdot</m> to the subset <m>H\subseteq G</m>, it is easy to see that it inherits the group axiom properties of <m>\cdot</m>. 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            For example, since <m>g_1(g_2g_3)=(g_1g_2)g_3</m> for <em>all</em> elements <m>g_1,g_2,g_3\in G</m>, it is certainly true for all <m>g_1,g_2,g_3\in H</m>. Thus <m>\boldsymbol{\cdot}_H</m> is associative.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Similarly, since by definition <m>e\in H</m> and <m>e</m> is the identity with respect to <m>\cdot</m>, it is also is an identity element with respect to <m>\boldsymbol{\cdot}_H</m>. The same argument shows that the inverse of an element of <m>H</m> with respect to <m>\cdot</m> is also an inverse with respect to <m>\boldsymbol{\cdot}_H</m>; since by definition <m>H</m> is closed under the inverse operations, all elements of <m>H</m> have inverses with respect to <m>\boldsymbol{\cdot}_H</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </proof>
    </proposition>
    <example xml:id="eg_">
    <title>Examples</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                Given a group <m>G</m> the subsets <m>\{e\}</m> and <m>G</m> itself are both easily seen to be subgroups. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                For all <m>n\in \Z</m>, the set <m>H=\{m\in \Z\mid n\mid m\}</m> is a subgroup of <m>\Z</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                For all <m>n\in \Z</m>, the set <m>\{nk\mid k\in \Z_{\geq 0}\}</m> is <em>not</em> a subgroup. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                For any group <m>G</m> and element <m>g\in G</m>, the subset <m>H=\{g^n\mid n\in \Z\}</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    </example>
    <definition xml:id="d_cyclic_groups">
    <title>Cyclic groups</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Given a group <m>G</m> and element <m>g\in G</m>, the subgroup <m>H=\{g^n\mid n\in \Z\}</m> is the <term>cyclic group generated by <m>g</m></term>, denoted <m>\angvec{g}</m>. 
    </p>
    <p>
        A group <m>G</m> is <term>cyclic</term> if <m>G=\angvec{g}</m> for some <m>g\in G</m>. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <example xml:id="eg_cyclic_groups">
    <title>Cyclic groups</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Decide which of the following groups are cyclic. If the example is a family of groups, decide whether all elements of the family are cyclic or not. 
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>\Z</m>
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>D_n</m>
            </p>
        </li>
        
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>\Z/n\Z</m>
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m>
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
    <p>
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                Since <m>\Z=\angvec{1}</m>, <m>\Z</m> is cyclic. 
            </p>
        </li>
        
    </ol>
    </p>
    </solution>
    </example>
